Title:
T(ROP)H: Thread Hijacking with ROP (Thread Hijacking without Executable Memory Allocation)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This post demonstrates a Windows x64 thread-hijacking DLL injection technique that avoids allocating RWX (or otherwise executable) memory in a remote process, reducing a common injection IOC. Instead of writing shellcode and redirecting RIP to it, the author builds a minimal ROP chain to call `LoadLibraryA` inside an existing remote thread. The key challenge addressed is that `SetThreadContext` can’t directly set volatile registers like `RCX` (needed for the first argument in the Windows x64 calling convention), so a `pop rcx; ret` gadget is used to load the DLL path pointer from the hijacked thread’s stack. The walkthrough covers finding a suitable gadget (e.g., in `ntdll.dll`), writing the DLL path into remote memory, suspending the thread, adjusting `RIP/RSP`, writing the ROP stack frame, and resuming execution. It’s useful for red teamers/pentesters and malware developers exploring stealthier injection tradeoffs, and for defenders understanding how “no RWX” injection can still occur. The post also notes detectability remains high due to `SetThreadContext` generating ETW telemetry (Kernel-Audit-API-Calls and Threat-Intelligence providers).

Technical Focus:
- Windows x64 calling convention (RCX argument passing) and volatile registers
- Thread hijacking via `SuspendThread` / `GetThreadContext` / `SetThreadContext` / `ResumeThread`
- ROP gadget discovery and runtime address resolution (e.g., `pop rcx; ret` in `ntdll.dll`)
- DLL injection via `LoadLibraryA` with remote `VirtualAllocEx` + `WriteProcessMemory` (RW only)
- Stack pivoting/stack frame setup for ROP (RSP adjustment, return chaining to `ExitThread`)
- ETW-based detection of `SetThreadContext` usage

Use Cases:
- DLL injection without remote executable memory allocation (avoid RWX heuristics)
- Proof-of-concept process injection research and tradeoff evaluation vs classic shellcode hijacking
- Building/validating detections for thread-context tampering and ROP-based execution
- Adversary emulation scenarios focusing on “living-off-existing-code” execution patterns

Keywords:
Windows x64, thread hijacking, ROP, return-oriented programming, SetThreadContext, GetThreadContext, SuspendThread, ResumeThread, RIP, RSP, RCX, pop rcx; ret, LoadLibraryA, ExitThread, VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, ntdll.dll, kernel32.dll, ETW, Microsoft-Windows-Threat-Intelligence